I think the answer is pretty obvious, an MMA fighter has more in his toolkit than a boxer does. If you take someone that's trained in many different fighting styles and put them up against someone that knows a single one, given that they're relatively the same skill level level the fighter with more knowledge will almost always win. Boxing is just one of the martial arts, whereas MMA is many, combined so the MMA fighter has a huge advantage.

Even though Tyson is way bigger, if he's taken to the ground he'll probably have a hard time defending himself. Boxing is good for fighting normal people and also other boxers, but if you go against an MMA fighter you're probably going to have a bad time.

That means in earlier primate forms, then yea it doesnt make sense for them to strike, let alone go for a submission because even if they grapple a lot they would be so fast-twitch they could explode out of most positions. However even if a lion's natural instinct is to bite, as like a chimp, that can still be abaused with our intelligence (look how african warriors will go out in the desert and stick their arm in a lions mouth or maybe choke out lions to then kill it). The complexity of the brain and instincts however is probably much more abstract and difficult to shape through evolution, in the sense that its better to learn how to use one's body efficiently, and biting is not the answer to a trained fighter 4/5 times.

Honestly, i always thought that the original had room for improvement, i love the monogram, and wish they'd use only it in the kits, similar to how some teams do it, like Flamengo, Rangers, etc.

I've never liked the excessive amount of borders, there's a smaller gold one, then a light blue one, then a black one, then there's the inside area in gold again, and the monogram in white, which to me makes it harder for the monogram to stand out, it also makes it so gold is the main color, which doesn't seem right to me, the internal area should be a different color.

So overall i like some of the changes, the darker blue, the smaller number of borders, the monogram in white standing out more from a dark blue background... The main problem to me is that they've made the monogram itself worse, much worse, the "I" and the "M" look much weirder and less polished, also the "C" is subtituted by an "O", which isn't even in the name, and the "F" is gone, overall it looks less elegant and interesting, so it's a downgrade for me.

com:
Biggest problem with this is that for Ice hockey, basketball and baseball international competition literally means nothing. and performance in the NHL, NBA and MLB is what is used to asses how good or bad a player is

>ice hockey
The winter Olympics is really the only time international competition matters and even then, this runs into some troubles because during the 2018 Olympics Gary Bettman completely prohibited NHL players from attending so a bunch of amateur athletes showed up. Outside of the Olympics most IIHF tournaments are very irrelevant and do not have participation from the best players.
>basketball
Again, the only time international basketball ever matters is at the Olympics and even then, it is typically just the USA team fucking around dominating everyone because they are miles above everyone else when it comes to the sport. When it comes to international competition outside of the Olympics people give ZERO Fucks. To shed light on this, consider that Pau Gasol has won two world cups with Spain yet these accomplishments go completely unrecognized on his resume as people tend to only focus on what he did as an NBA player and nothing else.
>baseball
Probably the best example of the three, first the way the WBSC does their world rankings is by taking average of all teams for that nation rather then just focusing on the mens senior team. They focus on youth teams like u13, u17, u19, and u21 and average that with the mens senior team to come up with their world rankings. The next biggest issues is there has LITERALLY never been a serious international competition in the sport of baseball. Olympic baseball takes place in the summer when the MLB is going on so no top player actually shows up only amateur athletes and even outside of the Olympics international competition in baseball has never actually featured the best players.

>>105931762
>they have a spine of world class players

That's because they develop their own players and their leagues are much more homegrown. Other than France, the three examples you use all have players playing in their own leagues and, by coincidence, those same two all have players playing for the same domestic team.
I'm not sure if I can explain it the way I want to, but it's sort of an economics based thing. The Premier League is the best league in the world because it buys the best players it can from everywhere it can. Other countries, likely because of finances, develop their own.
Therefore we'll buy players from Spain, from Germany, from France etc, but they don't buy ours. Rather than developing our own players we "pay clubs" to develop players and then buy them from them once they're developed. The only exception being younger players who we buy from abroad and develop based on their potential.
So while French youth players are competing against other French youth players for starts in their domestic sides, Spanish against Spanish etc, English players are competing against youth players from all over the world for starts in their domestic sides and more often than not the foreign bought player is kept on because of the outlay and because they've been identified as having higher potential while the English player is released.
While a French club might have someone with potential bought by a club like Chelsea, an English player with potential drops down the divisions (like Vardy for example) because foreign clubs don't buy them.
It's why we have strong domestic teams, but foreign countries have strong NTs. You can't really have both unless you balance it correctly.
It's similar economics with "overpriced" British players. It's not that their prices are inflated entirely because they're British. It's because they qualify as HG which you need X amount of in your squad. But because fewer are developed the best ones come at a higher premium.

It's not a total crapshoot.

Scouting and analytics are pretty good at identifying two things - certain kinds of likely busts, and competent role players. So being good at scouting allows you to avoid making certain kinds of obvious mistakes, or to put it another way, allows you to avoid being the Knicks. And it also allows you to get a lot of useful role players, like the Celtics or Spurs or Grizzlies do.

But outside of those things, it is a crapshoot. And it also depends a lot on the developmental structure you have in place.

VAR has made it so that we can review situations that were never seen before or ignored. The technology is not fit to referee the rules it is supposed to because it's too advanced and the old method of relying on the ref's eyes led for some leeway. VAR can be too accurate and the rules haven't kept up with the level of accuracy. Like handballs. Before, if a handball wasn't seen or clear no foul was given but now, because we can see a ball fractionally hit the lower arm, we immediately jump to "foul!" regardless of whether or not it was blasted at someone or chipped into their arm from point blank range. In the past, the ref wouldn't waved it on as "didn't look purposeful" but now they feel obliged to assume intent because, if they don't, fans will get buttmad that "it did touch the arm though!!!"

com:
The most obnoxious thing about Tom Brady is that he isn't as good as many of his contemporaries. And let's not compare Brady's SB performances with that of his supposed predecessor, Joe Montana. The disparity between their passer ratings is frankly embarrassing. And it's embarrassing for the whole sport. Because the purported "GOAT's" of the other leagues don't unravel under the microscope. It's simply impossible to contend that Babe Ruth, Wayne Gretzky, and Michael Jordan weren't astronomically better than their peers. They revolutionized their respective games to such a degree, they made a mockery of the very notion of competition. Whereas Brady doesn't survive statistical scrutiny, and he doesn't pass the eye-test.

And you know what the worst part is? In a few of those throws last night, I saw in Mahomes something I haven't seen in a long time: a blinding spark of athletic brilliance. It was genuinely reminiscent of watching Jordan pirouette through a whole team before launching himself into the air. Leaving you with the sense that you'd just witnessed something impossible. Granted, football is a much different sport, with a much different structure. But that sort of surreal shit is the whole reason I watch. And now, to my dying day, people will insist that Brady was the better QB. Tragic, and ridiculous.

It's really a lot of things, but mostly it's an accumulation of 20 years of the highest level of football knowledge while still maintaining excellent physical ability, and having probably the most extreme halo effect ever seen in at least American sports.

From a pure football standpoint, he has taken such good care of himself that he still throws extremely well, amazing pocket awareness to never put himself in bad physical situations (that most young dual threat QBs are pushed to do). Pair this with talking about defenses with Bill Belichick for almost 20 years, and you probably know more than virtually all offensive coordinators or coaches in the league about dissecting the game. He's able to make in-game defensive reads and adjustments that basically no other quarterback can today. The closest comparison would be someone like Peyton Manning at the end of his career, who for all intents and purposes was the OC of the Broncos, but Peyton's body was so destroyed by the end that he could barely throw a football. Tom is still elite.

The second is that his halo effect is unreal, and that's something that only has snowballed over the years. His ability to brainwash players and get them to buy into whatever he is doing is unparalleled. He's no joke like a cult leader. The guy is universally loved by everyone he plays with: murderers, rapists, psychos, whatever. Look at guys like Antonio Brown, compltely out of control and essentially blacklisted from the NFL. Turned his career around, no diva behavior, no ego, no bullshit on the Bucs.

You can't be an NBA player if you're five foot, three inches, for example. You have to reach a certain baseline. But once you have reached that minimum mandatory baseline of athletic ability, and you have an extraordinary advantage in technical skills and anticipatory instincts and knowledge, you can compensate for a huge deficiency in athletics talent. Obviously some sorts and positions depend more on athleticism than others. But even in those sports, this principle still remains true. It's incredible that most fans and even scouts, general managers and coaches still fail to understand this.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CsgnGyabJf8

>>105948044
>>105948082
You don't understand pontos corridos. You see, there's a reason it's so widespread around the world.
Football is, first and foremost, entertainment. If you have only cups, a lot of teams would be eliminated before the end, and supporters would be left unentertained. It used to be like this before, so clubs and federations had to make up for this with soulless friendlies and meme tournaments for teams which nothing left to compete for.
Pontos corridos solve this issue because all teams have matches throughout the full season. It's better than friendlies/meme tournaments because every team has something to fight for in pontos corridos. The best fight for the title and copalib spots; the mid table fight for sudakino spots; the shitters fight against relegation. Yes, sometimes a team wins the trophy before the end, but we still have teams fighting for copalib/sudakino/relegation until the end.
And even if you think brasileirão has no emotion, we still have cdb, copalib and sudakino. Plenty of soul cups.

1. Because it knows it isn't ready for it - if they don't get the spot, then it was better they didn't, because it's a squad in dire needs of rebuild.

2. They have the chips on fighting the championship, which is important symbolically as it has the name of one of the most beloved players. Adding a match to the schedule won't help, and this is a heavily injury-prone squad. The only actual playmaker there is is already out. So, instead of rushing an extra match they aren't even confident on winning, they rather keep building up and see what they get.

I'm actually a Peñarol supporter and would rather see them go to Sudamericana. It's the Libertadores that destroyed us: we know we can't realistically fight for it but incur in debt and bad decisions doing so.
